# Valve Control, Flow/Pressure Management & Data Trending

## 1. Control valve management
Control valves regulate flow or pressure by modulating opening position
(0-100%) based on a PID controller output — distinct from on/off pumps,
valves allow fine, continuous control.

| Aspect | Detail |
|---|---|
| Valve type | Modulating control valve (e.g. globe or butterfly, electric or pneumatic actuator) |
| Control signal | 4-20mA or 0-10V position command from PID controller |
| Position feedback | 4-20mA position transmitter, closes the loop for accurate positioning |
| Valve characteristic | Equal-percentage or linear, selected based on process (equal-% common for flow control with variable pressure drop) |
| Fail-safe position | Fail-open or fail-closed on air/power loss, chosen per process safety requirement (e.g. dosing valve typically fails closed) |

### Valve commissioning checks
1. Verify full stroke (0-100%) matches actual physical travel
2. Verify fail-safe action on loss of signal/air/power
3. Check for valve hysteresis (difference between commanded and actual
   position going up vs. down) — excessive hysteresis degrades control loop
   performance
4. Tune associated PID loop only after valve stroke/response is verified —
   a sticking or oversized valve will fight good tuning

## 2. Flow control loop
- **PV:** Flow rate (magnetic flow meter or equivalent)
- **Final control element:** Control valve (or VFD-driven pump, depending on
  application)
- **Control note:** Valve-based flow control depends on valve characteristic
  matching the process — equal-percentage valves linearize flow response
  when pressure drop varies significantly across the operating range

## 3. Pressure control loop
- **PV:** Pressure (pressure transmitter, upstream or downstream depending
  on application — e.g. maintaining discharge pressure or backpressure)
- **Final control element:** Control valve or VFD-driven pump
- **Control note:** Pressure loops tend to be fast — tuning favors slightly
  more conservative gain than flow loops to avoid valve hunting/oscillation

## 4. Data trending & historian (timestamped data)
A SCADA historian records process values with timestamps, enabling trend
analysis over time — critical for troubleshooting, compliance reporting, and
spotting slow degradation (e.g. valve wear, sensor drift) that isn't visible
in real-time values alone.

### What gets trended
| Data point | Why it's trended |
|---|---|
| Flow, level, pressure (PV vs SP) | Verify control loop performance over time, spot oscillation or drift |
| Valve position | Detect valve wear (increasing position needed for same flow = wear or fouling) |
| pH, chlorine, turbidity | Compliance reporting, process performance history |
| Pump run status/amperage | Detect increasing load over time (bearing wear, blockage) — links to `pump-maintenance-program.md` |
| Alarms (timestamped) | Root-cause analysis after an upset — correlate alarm sequence with trend data |

### Implementation (Ignition SCADA)
- Historian tags configured for each key process value, with an appropriate
  logging rate (e.g. every 10-30 sec for fast loops, every few minutes for
  slow trends like tank level over a day)
- Trend screens built in Ignition showing PV/SP/output overlay for each
  control loop, with timestamp-based zoom/pan for troubleshooting
- Alarm history logged with timestamp, allowing correlation with trend data
  during incident review

